=========================================
C++ std::list (Doubly Linked List)
INTERVIEW NOTES (CLEAN & FINAL)
=========================================

1. What is std::list?
----------------------
- std::list is a Doubly Linked List in STL.
- Each element is stored in a node.

Node structure:
[data | prev | next]

Example:
10 <-> 20 <-> 30

-----------------------------------------

2. Internal Implementation (VERY IMPORTANT)
------------------------------------------
- Implemented as a Doubly Linked List.
- Each node contains:
  1. data
  2. pointer to previous node
  3. pointer to next node

Memory is NON-CONTIGUOUS:

NULL <- [10] <-> [20] <-> [30] -> NULL

👉 Nodes are stored anywhere in memory.

-----------------------------------------

3. Why use list?
-----------------
Vector problem:

[10 20 30 40]
Insert 25 → shifting required → O(n)

List:

10 <-> 20 <-> 30 <-> 40
Insert 25 → only pointer changes → O(1)

✔ No shifting of elements
✔ Efficient insert/delete at known position

-----------------------------------------

4. Complexity (VERY IMPORTANT)
-----------------------------
insert (known position)   -> O(1)
erase (known position)    -> O(1)
push_front / push_back    -> O(1)
pop_front / pop_back      -> O(1)
access by index           -> O(n)
search (find)             -> O(n)
size                      -> O(1)

-----------------------------------------

5. Random Access?
------------------
❌ Not supported: l[i]

Reason:
- Nodes are not stored in contiguous memory
- Need traversal from head

Complexity: O(n)

-----------------------------------------

6. Contiguous Memory?
---------------------
vector → contiguous ✔
deque  → segmented ✔
list   → non-contiguous ❌

Example:
[10] -> [20] -> [30] stored at random memory locations

-----------------------------------------

7. Iterator Stability (IMPORTANT)
----------------------------------
✔ Insert does NOT invalidate iterators
✔ Only erased element’s iterator becomes invalid

Reason:
- No shifting of elements
- Only pointer updates

-----------------------------------------

8. Why insert/erase is O(1)?
----------------------------
If iterator is given:

it -> 20

Insert 15:

10 <-> 15 <-> 20 <-> 30

Only pointer changes → O(1)

⚠ Finding position is O(n)

-----------------------------------------

9. list vs vector (VERY IMPORTANT)
----------------------------------

VECTOR:
- Contiguous memory
- Fast access O(1)
- Insert middle O(n)
- Fast traversal (cache friendly)

LIST:
- Non-contiguous memory
- No random access
- Insert/erase O(1) (if position known)
- Poor cache performance

👉 Vector is faster in most real systems due to cache locality

-----------------------------------------

10. Common Functions
--------------------
push_back()
push_front()
pop_back()
pop_front()
insert()
erase()
front()
back()
begin()
end()
size()
empty()
